blocks: <table class="user"><tr><td align="right">A <a class="url http outside" href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dahn_yoga">Dahn yoga</a> ad caught my eye several years ago in a local newspaper, and I've been carrying around a ragged-torn copy ever since. Somehow the <a class="url http outside" href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Lotus_position">lotus position</a>&mdash;calm, open, balanced, meditative, almost-but-not-quite symmetric&mdash;captivates my mind. <em>(Or maybe it's just the exaggerated feminine shape of the artwork?!)</em> Likewise <a class="url http outside" href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mudra">mudras</a>, symbolic hand-gestures, enchant me. A Parvati as Boga Shakti statue that my wife brought home some time ago, for instance, has fingers held in a mudra, representing I know not what. Fascinating! <em>(Or maybe it's justy the exaggerated feminine shape of the artwork?!)</em><p>So do certain postures have an ability to modify mental states, intrinsically or via association? Can moving or posing a certain way produce profound health benefits, physical or spiritual? Or is this all mere mysticism, the common fantasy of something-for-nothing? Sit this way, hold your hands that way, and take a shortcut to wisdom, peace, happiness? One wonders ...</p></td><td align="center"><img class="url http" src="http://zhurnaly.com/images/Yoga_Lotus_Dahn_ad.jpg" alt="http://zhurnaly.com/images/Yoga_Lotus_Dahn_ad.jpg" /></td></tr></table><p><em><strong>^z</strong></em> - 2010-08-08</p>
