text: | A [[http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dahn_yoga|Dahn yoga]] ad caught my eye several years ago in a local newspaper, and I've been carrying around a ragged-torn copy ever since. Somehow the [[http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Lotus_position|lotus position]]&mdash;calm, open, balanced, meditative, almost-but-not-quite symmetric&mdash;captivates my mind. //(Or maybe it's just the exaggerated feminine shape of the artwork?!)//  Likewise [[http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mudra|mudras]], symbolic hand-gestures, enchant me. A Parvati as Boga Shakti statue that my wife brought home some time ago, for instance, has fingers held in a mudra, representing I know not what. Fascinating! //(Or maybe it's justy the exaggerated feminine shape of the artwork?!)// 
	
	So do certain postures have an ability to modify mental states, intrinsically or via association? Can moving or posing a certain way produce profound health benefits, physical or spiritual? Or is this all mere mysticism, the common fantasy of something-for-nothing? Sit this way, hold your hands that way, and take a shortcut to wisdom, peace, happiness? One wonders ... | http://zhurnaly.com/images/Yoga_Lotus_Dahn_ad.jpg |
	
	//**^z**// - 2010-08-08
	
